<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/27247586-katie"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1494793009i/27247586._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/27247586-katie">Katie</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">There&apos;s one small romance, but it&apos;s very short, ungraphic, and irrelevant to the overall plot. Seems almost like it was just kind of thrown in there b<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">There's one small romance, but it's very short, ungraphic, and irrelevant to the overall plot. Seems almost like it was just kind of thrown in there because she thought it needed one. But I found it refreshing to read a book who's driving force wasn't romance for once.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
