<span id="freeTextContainer17088068098828941457">Well at the risk of sounding like Veruca Salt, I want a dragon and I want one now!<br/><br/>This is the second book lately that I have thoroughly enjoyed despite not much actually happening. How can not much happen in a book where dragons fight in the Napoleonic wars you ask? Well, the author can focus on the hatching, training, and building up of the relationships between our main character and his dragon. But I was there for it. Temeraire is such a wonderful dragon and I loved the connection that develo</span>
  <span id="freeText17088068098828941457" style="display:none">Well at the risk of sounding like Veruca Salt, I want a dragon and I want one now!<br /><br />This is the second book lately that I have thoroughly enjoyed despite not much actually happening. How can not much happen in a book where dragons fight in the Napoleonic wars you ask? Well, the author can focus on the hatching, training, and building up of the relationships between our main character and his dragon. But I was there for it. Temeraire is such a wonderful dragon and I loved the connection that developed between him and Captain Laurence. Naomi decided to maintain the misogynistic views held during this time period but went some way to showing that 'girls can do anything' which included riding dragons that will rain hellfire upon their enemies. A great series opener!</span>
  <a data-text-id="17088068098828941457" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

